Get the results, check for the clusters¶

In [12]:
# Import KMeans
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Inertia is the sum of squared error for each cluster.
# Therefore the smaller the inertia the denser the cluster(closer together all the points are)
inertia = []
# The Silhouette Score is from -1 to 1
# Show how close or far away the clusters are from each other
# How dense the clusters are.
# The closer your silhouette score is to 1 the more distinct your clusters are.
KMsc = []
KMy_hat_results = []
    
# change the number of clusters
for i in range(2, 11):
    
    # prediction of clusters
    KMean = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=21)
    KMean.fit(Iris)
    y_hat = KMean.predict(Iris)
    
    inertia.append((i, KMean.inertia_))
    KMsc.append((i, silhouette_score(Iris, y_hat)))
    KMy_hat_results.append((i, y_hat))
    
    # scatter plot the petal length (column 2), petal width (column 3)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.scatterplot(Iris['petal length (cm)'], Iris['petal width (cm)'], hue=y_hat, palette = 'Paired', s=50)
    # Add title
    plt.title('When n_clusters={}'.format(i))
    # show centroid centres as grey circle opacity 50%
    centers = KMean.cluster_centers_
    plt.scatter(centers[:, 2], centers[:, 3], c='black', s=200, alpha=0.5)
    plt.show()

# Clustering silhouette_score
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

X = Iris

for n_cluster in range(2, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_cluster).fit(X)
    label = kmeans.labels_
    sil_coeff = silhouette_score(X, label, metric='euclidean')
    print("For n_clusters={}, The Silhouette Coefficient is {}".format(
            n_cluster, sil_coeff))

# Gaussian Mixture model
from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture as GMM
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

aicbic = []
# The Silhouette Score is from -1 to 1
# Show how close or far away the clusters are from each other
# How dense the clusters are.
# The closer your silhouette score is to 1 the more distinct your clusters are.
GMMsc = []
GMMy_hat_results = []

# change the number of clusters
for i in range(2, 11):
    
    # prediction of clusters
    gmm = GMM(i)
    gmm.fit(Iris)
    y_hat = gmm.predict(Iris)
    
    aicbic.append((i, gmm.aic(Iris), gmm.bic(Iris)))
    GMMsc.append((i, silhouette_score(Iris, y_hat)))
    GMMy_hat_results.append((i, y_hat))
    
    # scatter plot the petal length (column 2), petal width (column 3)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.scatterplot(Iris['petal length (cm)'], Iris['petal width (cm)'], hue=y_hat, palette = 'Paired', s=50)
    # Add title
    plt.title('When n_clusters={}'.format(i))
    plt.show()

For Score and Evaluate Model¶

Hierarchical - AgglomerativeClustering¶

Agglomerative: this method starts with each sample being a different cluster and then merging them by the ones that are closer from each other until there is only one cluster.

  1. Do a dendrogram - To better understand the agglomeration process, it is a useful graphical method called a dendrogram, which shows in a static way how the aggregations are performed, starting from the bottom (where all samples are separated) till the top (where the linkage is complete)
  2. From the graph to determine the number of clusters
  3. Compare against actual plot.
  4. Determine which number of clusters matches the actual plot the most
  5. What is the best number of clusters in Hierarchical
In [899]:
# Plot dendrogram for hierarchical clustering
# The clades are arranged according to how similar (or dissimilar) they are.
# Clades that are close to the same height are similar to each other; 
# clades with different heights are dissimilar — the greater the difference in height, 
# the more dissimilarity (you can measure similarity in many different ways;
import scipy.cluster.hierarchy as shc

plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))
sns.set(style='white')
shc.dendrogram(shc.linkage(Iris, method='ward'))
plt.ylabel('Euclidean Distance', fontsize = 15)
plt.xlabel('Iris', fontsize = 15)
plt.title("Dendrogram for hierarchical clustering", fontsize = 20)
plt.show()

print("We get 3 clusters by our dendrogram as shown in the figure above.")
print("Height in dendrogram at which two clusters are merged represents the distance between two clusters in data space.")

We get 3 clusters by our dendrogram as shown in the figure above.
Height in dendrogram at which two clusters are merged represents the distance between two clusters in data space.

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16,8))
sns.scatterplot(Iris['petal length (cm)'], Iris['petal width (cm)'], hue=Iris['class'], s=50, palette = 'Paired', ax=axes[0])
sns.scatterplot(Iris['petal length (cm)'], Iris['petal width (cm)'], hue=ACy_hat, s=50, palette = 'Paired', ax=axes[1])
axes[0].set_title('Actual', fontsize=18)
axes[1].set_title('Hierarchical - AgglomerativeClustering', fontsize=18)
plt.show()

# GMM
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(26, 8))

# gradient
GMMclusters = [x[0] for x in aicbic]
GMMaic = [x[1] for x in aicbic]
GMMbic = [x[2] for x in aicbic]
GMMsc = [x[1] for x in GMMsc]

# plot them
ax[0].plot(GMMclusters, y_aic, 'rx-', label='AIC')
ax[0].plot(GMMclusters, y_bic, 'gx-', label='BIC')
ax[0].set_xlabel('Number of Clusters', fontsize = 15)
ax[0].set_ylabel('Gradient', fontsize = 15)
ax[0].legend(loc = 0)
ax[0].set_title('Gradient of AIC and BIC', fontsize = 20)


# plot silhouetter
ax[1].plot(GMMclusters, GMMsc, 'bx-')
ax[1].set_xlabel('Number of Clusters', fontsize = 15)
ax[1].set_ylabel('Silhouette score', fontsize = 15)
ax[1].set_title('Silhouette graph', fontsize = 20)
plt.show()

print("The optimal number of clusters is the value that minimizes the AIC or BIC, depending on which approximation we wish to use.")
print("The AIC tells us that our choice of 10 components is a little too much: around 5-6 components would have been a better choice.")
print("As is typical with this sort of problem, the BIC recommends a simpler model.")
print("And having a lower gradient is a better score, so it suggests the best value for k is 3.")
print("From the silhouette score, we can observe that the 'elbow' is located at 5")
print("However, the elbow shown is not obvious. So we can interpret that the number of clusters we conclude as the best would be 2-4.")

The optimal number of clusters is the value that minimizes the AIC or BIC, depending on which approximation we wish to use.
The AIC tells us that our choice of 10 components is a little too much: around 5-6 components would have been a better choice.
As is typical with this sort of problem, the BIC recommends a simpler model.
And having a lower gradient is a better score, so it suggests the best value for k is 3.
From the silhouette score, we can observe that the 'elbow' is located at 5

Conclusions¶

Algorithms used:¶


K-means clustering
Hierarchical Clustering
Gaussian mixture models

Test your clustering with different possible values of k:¶


For all algorithms, values of k would be 2 to 10. Based on the pairplot, there are at least 2 groups of data points in most of the plots. So, the least value of k would be 2.

Determine the best possible value of k. And how to determine that this is the best value for k¶

KMeans - plotting a graph to determine the possible values of k based on inertia and silhouette score using elbow method.
For inertia elbow plot - best possible values of k: 2 - 3
For silhouette elbow plot - best possible values of k: 2 - 4 (after testing k = 2 or 3 against actual, there's no need to test for k = 4)

Hierarchical(Agglomerative) - plotting a dendrogram to determine the possible values if k.
From the dendrogram - best possible values of k: 3

Gaussian Mixture Models - plotting a graph Akaike information criterion(AIC) and Bayesian information criterion (BIC) against number of clusters. And plotting plot of silhoutte score against number of clusters using elbow method.
From the gradient graph - best possible values of k: 3
For silhouette elbow plot - best possible values of k: 2 -4 (But after testing K = 3 against actual, there's no need to test for k = 4)

All suggested k = 3.¶

Determine the best model¶

Based on the score from the 3 models:¶


K-means clustering - 99.33%
Hierarchical Clustering - 33.33% (The clustering into data group is accurate however classifies the wrong class name to wrong data group.)
Gaussian mixture models - 100%
From here, I can conclude that Gaussian mixture model is the most suitable model for this problem out of the 3.
